\details{
Synonym pairs are item pairs whose whole-sample inter-item correlation exceeds
\code{critical_r} (default \code{0.60}). Pairing uses raw responses with no reverse-scoring,
so a reverse-keyed item (negative correlations) is never a synonym (it may be an
antonym instead). The score is the single correlation across all qualifying pairs'
stacked values.

\code{critical_r} is a property of the inventory: on broad personality inventories the
strongest inter-item correlations can fall below \code{0.60}, so no pairs qualify, every
value is \code{NA}, and the index abstains with a warning. Lower \code{critical_r}, or use a
more homogeneous scale.

The default cutoff flags the lowest-consistency respondents at the \code{fpr} quantile
(5th percentile), flagging at least \code{fpr} of respondents rather than a calibrated
false-positive rate. A respondent with fewer than three complete synonym pairs, or
zero-variance pair values (a straightliner), has no defined correlation
(\code{value}/\code{flagged} are \code{NA}).
}
\section{What this catches}{

Random and partial / changepoint responding. It misses pure straightlining and
midpoint locking (a constant row abstains); pair it with \code{\link[=cier_longstring]{cier_longstring()}} and
\code{\link[=cier_irv]{cier_irv()}}.
}

\section{Pairing reference on contaminated samples}{

When much of the sample responds carelessly the inter-item correlations shrink and
no pair clears \code{critical_r}, so the index abstains exactly when carelessness is
highest. Supplying \code{reference} discovers pairs on a clean source while every
respondent is still scored on the full analysis sample. Because \code{critical_r = 0.60}
is strict, this workflow usually supplies a clean \code{reference} and relaxes
\code{critical_r} (e.g. to \code{0.40}). \code{reference = NULL} (default) is whole-sample
self-pairing.
}

